  <div class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-700 mb-2">Obstacle Recognition for Lower-Limb Exoskeleton Control using Computer Vision and Deep Learning</div>

  <div class="w-full" style="margin-top: 0px; text-align: justify;">
    
    <p>
      In this project, we developed a computer vision and AI-based perception system for obstacle detection in lower-limb exoskeletons. 
	  Using a combination of depth sensors, LiDAR, and machine learning (ML) algorithms, the research focuses on real-time object recognition to enhance exoskeleton-assisted mobility. 
	  A key component is sensor fusion, which integrates multiple sensor inputs to improve detection accuracy and adaptability in various environments. 
	  Additionally, Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) are used to process visual data, allowing the exoskeleton to recognize and classify obstacles, which contributes to 
	  safer and more adaptive robotic-assisted movement. Experimental and test results show that the system is accurate and reliable in terms of obstacle detection and distance measurement, 
	  demonstrating its potential for further development.
      
