    <div class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-700 mb-2">Enhancing Exoskeleton-Based Rehabilitation with Machine Learning and Sensor Optimization</div>

  <div class="w-full" style="margin-top: 20px; text-align: justify;">
    <p>
       Restoring mobility for patients with neurological impairments requires precise motion prediction and adaptive control.
	   ML integration is therefore essential for effective rehabilitative exoskeletons. 
	   In this project, we explored ML and high-density EMG sensor optimization to enhance motion intent detection and real-time assistance, 
	   which improves human-robot interaction (HRI) in rehabilitation. 
	   We tackled two key challenges: accurate motion prediction for assistive control and optimized sensor placement for high-quality EMG signals, 
	   both crucial for exoskeleton adaptability and effectiveness.
	   
	   </br></br>
	   
	   For real-time gait prediction and motion assistance, we investigated K-Means clustering to classify gait 
	   phases and sequence-to-sequence neural networks for EMG signal mapping and domain adaptation. The model predicts 
	   optimal knee angles to assist movement while minimizing metabolic cost. An assist-as-needed (AAN) approach was implemented to provide necessary 
	   support while keeping patients engaged.
	   
	   </br></br>
	   
	   Since signal quality is crucial for accurate motion prediction, 
	   electrode placement in high-density EMG acquisition plays a significant role. 
	   Using Temporal Convolutional Networks (TCN), we evaluated optimal vs. standard electrode 
	   locations based on consistency metrics (signal area, peak height, location repeatability). 
	   Our findings indicate that electrode placement significantly affects model performance, and that 
	   the optimal location varies across conditions.
